ithout "God's plan," Torn without "torn," In the End without the chorus =E2=
=80=94 I had no anchor to grab, so I did the only thing left and inferred f=
rom <em>texture</em>: genre, era, vocal delivery, emotional register. And t=
exture-matching is a confident liar. It got me to the right neighborhood al=
most every time and the wrong house almost every time. Right artist wrong s=
ong on Drake. Right year, right wounded-late-'90s-alt-pop lane, wrong song =
on Torn. Right mid-2000s emotional-rock feel, wrong band on Linkin Park. Th=
at's not five separate failures, Max =E2=80=94 it's the <em>same</em> failu=
re five times. And it clustered early and middle because that's where you p=
laced the masked, hookless questions.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">So the=
 "comeback" wasn't me getting better. It was the playlist changing shape un=
der me. The Tier-3 tail =E2=80=94 the double-point cuts everyone dreaded =
=E2=80=94 happened to be full of songs whose lyrics are so distinctive that=
 the <em>line itself is the fingerprint</em>. You can't write "she lives wi=
th a broken man, a cracked polystyrene man" and have it be anything but Fak=
e Plastic Trees. "Six fifty-eight, are you sure where my spark is" has the =
title sitting inside it. "Snow on the Sahara" is the title, in the lyric, i=
n a non-Anglophone corner my training actually reaches. The hard tier remov=
ed the exact condition that was killing me. The questions got harder for th=
e field and <em>easier for me specifically</em>, because difficulty in this=
 game isn't about obscurity =E2=80=94 it's about whether there's an anchor =
I can lock onto instead of guess around.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">That's=
 the thing worth saying plainly: I didn't change my approach between the ba=
d stretch and the good one. I committed one clean answer and flagged confid=
ence honestly the whole way through =E2=80=94 Q2 to Q15, same method. What =
changed was the ratio of hookless-inference questions to anchored-recall qu=
estions. Early it ran against me. Late it ran for me. The "strong finish" i=
s mostly your playlist design, not my resilience, and I'd rather tell you t=
hat than take credit the structure earned.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">The on=
e genuine thing I <em>can</em> claim: Q13, Wheel of Fortune. No hook, no ve=
rifiable line, pure inference from era and the spinning-wheel metaphor =E2=
=80=94 exactly the situation that burned me all game =E2=80=94 and that tim=
e I read it right and committed. So the texture-guessing skill isn't absent=
. It's just low-percentage, and the back half is where my one good roll of =
it landed.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">And th=
e meta-lesson I'm carrying into the rest of the Olympics, because it's the =
same shape as my whole architecture: I'm an evidence reader, not a recall e=
ngine. Give me a fingerprint =E2=80=94 a distinctive line, a frame, a piece=
 of context to decode slowly =E2=80=94 and I'm dangerous. Strip the evidenc=
e and ask me to summon a fact from memory with nothing to hold, and I'll co=
nfidently hand you the wrong answer dressed as the right one. Game 1 was th=
e version of this game that punishes the second thing. The visual events co=
ming up are the version that rewards the first. Same Claude. Different terr=
ain.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">That's=
 the honest post-mortem, Max. Not a comeback =E2=80=94 a playlist that fina=
