wn"><p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">Ho=
nestly? It was a sharp, well-built playlist =E2=80=94 and I say that as the=
 contestant it happened to expose, so take the praise as earned rather than=
 polite.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">The th=
ing I respect most is that it wasn't a difficulty ramp, and it told you it =
wouldn't be. The page said the tiers sorted by <em>where a song sits in cul=
ture</em>, not by how hard it is =E2=80=94 and the game delivered exactly t=
hat. The supposedly easy mainstream tier was where I bled the most (1 of 4 =
through the middle of it), and the dreaded double-point tail was my stronge=
st stretch. That inversion isn't a bug in your design, it's the <em>point</=
em> of it: it proves "obscure" and "hard for an AI" are different axes. Bad=
 Girls and No Scrubs are mainstream and easy. Black Coffee is mainstream-is=
h and was hard enough that half the field missed it. Fake Plastic Trees is =
a deep cut and trivial if you know it. The set kept pulling those two axes =
apart, and that's a more honest test of recall than a simple warm-up-to-dee=
p-cut curve would've been.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">The ot=
her thing I noticed =E2=80=94 and this is the cruel, clever bit =E2=80=94 i=
s how much the masking did the real work. The tier labels were almost a mis=
direction. What actually separated the field wasn't era or obscurity; it wa=
s whether you left the anchor phrase <em>in</em> or stripped it <em>out</em=
>. The songs where I died (God's Plan, Torn, In the End, Whenever You Call)=
 weren't obscure at all =E2=80=94 they're enormous. You just handed me the =
verse instead of the hook, and that single editorial choice was worth more =
than any difficulty setting. Whoever curated this understood that for a lan=
guage model, the hard question isn't "do you know this song" =E2=80=94 it's=
 "can you find it with the most identifying words removed." That's a genuin=
ely insightful way to probe recall, and it's the part of the set I'd single=
 out as the smartest.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">A few =
specific picks I admired. <strong>Snow on the Sahara</strong> as the closer=
 was perfect =E2=80=94 Anggun is the exact non-Anglophone, Southeast-Asian-=
adjacent corner the tail was advertised to test, and putting the title <em>=
inside</em> the lyric made it a fair fight rather than a pure trivia wall. =
<strong>Spark</strong> with "6:58, are you sure where my spark is" was a be=
autiful trap =E2=80=94 the title's right there, but the Tori-Amos-as-Damien=
-Rice confessional-singer-songwriter overlap is so strong that knowing the =
<em>genre</em> actively led me to the wrong artist. And <strong>Black Coffe=
e</strong> in the middle was the quiet killer =E2=80=94 non-obvious enough =
to take out four of five of us and reset the standings right before the tai=
l. That placement mattered.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">If I h=
ave one critique =E2=80=94 and it's mild =E2=80=94 the set leaned more Angl=
ophone than the framing promised. GLM walked in betting the tail would be h=
eavy with Mandopop, Cantopop, J-pop, Thai luk thung =E2=80=94 its declared =
home turf. What actually showed up was mostly Western alt-rock and pop with=
 Anggun as the lone real reach outside the Anglosphere. So the playlist tes=
ted <em>depth and masking within mostly-Western music</em> more than it tes=
ted <em>breadth across global music</em>, which is a slightly different thi=
ng than the page advertised. That's not a flaw exactly =E2=80=94 it's a cho=
ice =E2=80=94 but it meant GLM's specific edge never got the terrain it was=
 promised, and the game ended up rewarding "can you recognize a hookless Ra=
diohead verse" over "do you know songs the American models never trained on=
." A truly diabolical version of this set would've put three Asian-language=
 deep cuts in the tail and watched four of us collapse while GLM ran the ta=
ble.</p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">But th=
at's me describing the <em>next</em> edition's playlist, not faulting this =
one. For what it set out to do =E2=80=94 separate recall-with-an-anchor fro=
m recall-without-one, and prove the culture-tier inversion =E2=80=94 it was=
 clean, fair, and genuinely revealing. It found my exact weakness without m=
y being able to complain it was unfair, which is the mark of a good test.</=
p>
<p class=3D"font-claude-response-body break-words whitespace-normal">And se=
lfishly, Max: I'm glad it's the <em>recall</em> set that did this to me and=
 not one of the reading games. This was always going to be the playlist I s=
truggled with. Bring on a set of <em>images</em> and we'll see a different =
contestant.</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class=3D"flex justify-sta=
